{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nConfig PERSISTENCE + reconciler-READ are already solved: `resolve_jira_settings` (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli_subprocess.py`) resolves url/user/project through `load_config().jira.*` (typed `JiraConfig`, reading `rebar.toml [jira]` / `pyproject.toml [tool.rebar.jira]` / legacy `.rebar/config.conf`), with `JIRA_URL/USER/PROJECT` env overriding and `JIRA_API_TOKEN` env-only; `rebar bridge-probe` already validates credentials end-to-end. The ONLY missing piece is an INTERACTIVE onboarding UX.\n\n## What\nAdd an interactive `rebar jira-onboard` subcommand (intercept, like `rebar llm`/`reconcile`; owns its own `--help`) that detects existing Jira settings via `resolve_jira_settings`, prompts for missing url/user/project, persists them to the typed config, guides on the env-only token, and runs `bridge-probe` validation. Mirror the `rebar llm setup` precedent. New impl: `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py`.\n\n## Scope\n- New `rebar jira-onboard` CLI intercept (Python). Detect via `resolve_jira_settings()`. Prompt for missing url/user/project. Flags: `--url/--user/--project` (non-interactive), `--no-validate`, `--reset` (clears persisted jira keys).\n- Persist via a NEW minimal writer `write_jira_config(...)` in `src/rebar/config.py`. Token NEVER written.\n- Reuse `bridge-probe` as the post-onboard check.\n- Out: any new config read LAYER, persisting secrets, touching the reconciler read path.\n\n## Mechanism — config write (resolves prior BLOCK; G6/T1/T3/T9/E1/E2)\n- Add `write_jira_config(url, user, project, *, root=None, clear=False) -> Path` to `config.py`. Atomic (tmp file + `os.replace`).\n- **Dependency choice — justified.** rebar's core is deliberately stdlib-only (`engine dependencies = []`; only pyyaml/jsonschema/referencing in core). `tomlkit`/`tomli-w` are NOT added: that would regress the stdlib-only core for a single onboarding writer. The fragility the reviewer flags (surgically editing arbitrary comment-rich user TOML — inline tables, dotted keys, multiline strings) is AVOIDED ENTIRELY by NARROWING THE WRITE SURFACE, not by adding a TOML-writer dep.\n- **Write-surface narrowing = the key safety property.** The wizard NEVER edits a user-owned `pyproject.toml`. The write target is always a dedicated, REBAR-OWNED file:\n  - If a `rebar.toml` exists (or none of the project configs exist) → write/upsert its `[jira]` table. `rebar.toml` is owned and managed by rebar, so a line-oriented `[jira]`-section upsert on it is simple and fully testable (no arbitrary-TOML hazard).\n  - If the discovered project config is a `pyproject.toml` → do NOT touch it; create `rebar.toml` at the repo root instead (it takes READ precedence over pyproject per `_discover_project_config`'s walk order: rebar.toml first). So onboarding a pyproject-configured repo writes a fresh, minimal rebar.toml — no risk to the user's pyproject.\n  - If the discovered config is legacy `.rebar/config.conf` → line-upsert dotted `jira.url/user/project=` lines (trivially safe, line-oriented).\n- **`[jira]`-section upsert (rebar.toml)** is line-oriented on a rebar-owned file: read existing text, validate it parses with `tomllib` (a `TOMLDecodeError` → clear error, NO write), locate the `[jira]` header, replace its three keys / append the section if absent, preserving every other line. Only `url/user/project` are ever written.\n- Terminology fixed: `rebar.toml` uses `[jira]`; `pyproject.toml` uses `[tool.rebar.jira]` (and we never write the latter — we create rebar.toml).\n\n## Mechanism — validation env bridge (resolves prior BLOCK; T3)\n- `bridge-probe` (`jira-capability-probe.py`) reads `JIRA_URL/USER/PROJECT/API_TOKEN` from `os.environ`. `_bridge_probe()` (`__init__.py`) currently hardcodes `env=engine_env()` with no env-injection param. FIX: give `_bridge_probe(argv, *, extra_env=None)` an optional overlay merged onto `engine_env()`. The wizard re-resolves via `resolve_jira_settings()` and passes the resolved url/user/project as `extra_env`, so the probe sees what was just persisted. `JIRA_API_TOKEN` must be in the env; if absent, the wizard SKIPS the live probe with a clear \"export JIRA_API_TOKEN, then run `rebar bridge-probe`\" message (not a hard failure).\n\n## Failure / edge paths (resolves T6/E5/T4)\n- Empty input at a required prompt re-prompts; EOF/Ctrl-C aborts cleanly (exit 1, NO partial write — input collection completes before any write). Failing bridge-probe surfaces PROBE_FAIL and returns non-zero, but the persisted config is KEPT (write and validate are separate). Config-write `OSError` → reported, non-zero. Existing `rebar.toml` with a TOML syntax error → caught `TOMLDecodeError` → clear error, no write. `--no-validate` skips the probe. `--reset` removes the three jira keys (rebar.toml `[jira]` block / legacy dotted lines) and asks for confirmation unless `--yes`.\n- TOCTOU: this is a single-operator interactive onboarding tool; concurrent wizard runs are out of scope. `os.replace` guarantees no torn/partial file; the read-modify-write last-writer-wins window is documented in the writer docstring.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `rebar jira-onboard`: detects existing settings (via `resolve_jira_settings`), prompts for missing url/user/project, persists to the typed config, runs `bridge-probe` validation with resolved settings injected into the probe env (via the new `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)`).\n- [ ] Persistence uses the narrowed-surface rule: rebar-owned `rebar.toml` `[jira]` upsert (or create rebar.toml when only pyproject/none exists); legacy `.rebar/config.conf` dotted-key upsert; NEVER edits a user `pyproject.toml`. Atomic; preserves other content; a malformed existing rebar.toml is caught (no write).\n- [ ] `JIRA_API_TOKEN` is env-only (guidance shown; NEVER written to any config file); reuses `resolve_jira_settings`/`load_config().jira` (no new config layer).\n- [ ] `--url/--user/--project`, `--no-validate`, `--reset` (+`--yes`), and `--help` (`src/rebar/_cli/help/jira-onboard.txt`) supported; EOF/empty-input handled.\n- [ ] Documented: CLI `--help` text + a `rebar jira-onboard` mention in `docs/jira-sync-setup.md`.\n- [ ] Tests (`tests/unit/test_jira_onboard.py`): detect existing vs missing; persist writes url/user/project to rebar.toml `[jira]` (preserving other keys); create-rebar.toml when only pyproject exists (pyproject untouched); legacy conf upsert; token NEVER written; malformed rebar.toml caught; `--reset`; EOF/empty-input abort (no partial write); `--no-validate` skips probe; `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)` overlays env. Full suite green.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py` (new; wizard + entry `_jira_onboard`)\n- `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` (intercept wiring + `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)`)\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/jira-onboard.txt` (new)\n- `src/rebar/config.py` (new `write_jira_config`)\n- `docs/jira-sync-setup.md` (wizard mention)\n- `tests/unit/test_jira_onboard.py` (new)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782781778726002001,"uuid":"a6ce13e6-b206-44d6-8c83-2cfdaa668a62"}